    <briefdescription>
<para>This <computeroutput><ref refid="classAdaptableUnaryFunction" kindref="compound" external="/home/cgal-testsuite/cgal_doc_build/CGAL-4.13-I-128/doc/scripts/build_doc/doc_tags/Manual.tag">AdaptableUnaryFunction</ref></computeroutput> computes the unit part of a given ring element. </para>    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para> The mathematical definition of unit part is as follows: Two ring elements <formula id="34">$ a$</formula> and <formula id="35">$ b$</formula> are said to be associate if there exists an invertible ring element (i.e. a unit) <formula id="36">$ u$</formula> such that <formula id="37">$ a = ub$</formula>. This defines an equivalence relation. We can distinguish exactly one element of every equivalence class as being unit normal. Then each element of a ring possesses a factorization into a unit (called its unit part) and a unit-normal ring element (called its unit normal associate).</para><para>For the integers, the non-negative numbers are by convention unit normal, hence the unit-part of a non-zero integer is its sign. For a <computeroutput><ref refid="classField" kindref="compound">Field</ref></computeroutput>, every non-zero element is a unit and is its own unit part, its unit normal associate being one. The unit part of zero is, by convention, one.</para><para><xrefsect id="refines_1_refines000016"><xreftitle>Refines</xreftitle><xrefdescription><para><computeroutput><ref refid="classAdaptableUnaryFunction" kindref="compound" external="/home/cgal-testsuite/cgal_doc_build/CGAL-4.13-I-128/doc/scripts/build_doc/doc_tags/Manual.tag">AdaptableUnaryFunction</ref></computeroutput> </para></xrefdescription></xrefsect></para><para><simplesect kind="see"><para><computeroutput><ref refid="classAlgebraicStructureTraits" kindref="compound">AlgebraicStructureTraits</ref></computeroutput> </para></simplesect>
</para>    </detaileddescription>
